TRIP COMMENTS: Conducting surveys with landowner permission. This checklist covers a thorough survey of birds along the Pajaro River, from the San Benito County side, between Highway 25 and Highway 101. Seventeen species confirmed breeding. Twelve species of passerines nesting (or suspected of nesting) in the woody riparian vegetation were seen flying into adjacent agricultural fields to forage.

In 1996-1998 known as "Lake Mierda" by local Marines.--Conducting avian surveys once or twice monthly by slowly driving along settling pond roads and stopping at fixed points along the route.  Settling ponds were identified with numbers (1-10) and observations of birds assigned to a Pond.  Birds were identified and counted singly or by groups of 10s, 20s, 50s, or 100s.  We made every effort to not double-count birds.----During our wildlife inventory surveys 1996-1999, the sewage ponds and associated drainage ditches were probably in place for decades and lacked many of the modern regulatory and efficiency requirements found in modern WWTPs.  Ditches were mostly unlined and vegetated with cattail and riparian plants (e.g., salt cedar, Atriplex, willow) and provided habitat for wildlife.  Many of the "better" wildlife ponds and ditches were removed or cleaned toward the end of our survey efforts, were and lined just after we finished surveys.  The current WWTP is likely nothing like what it was in terms of providing habitat for migratory birds as it was prior to 1999.
